   "abstract": "Andrea Reid (Nisga'a) and colleagues argue that the usual call to integrate or incorporate Indigenous knowledge into Western science is often a euphemism for assimilation, and they offer Two-Eyed Seeing instead as an ethic of knowledge coexistence and complementarity. What sets Two-Eyed Seeing apart, they stress, is its action imperative: knowledge transforms the holder, who then bears a responsibility to act on it, which they trace through three Canadian fisheries case studies. For a student, this shows that when whose knowledge counts genuinely changes, the research and management themselves change.",
