   "abstract": "Debbie Martin (Inuk, NunatuKavut) presents Two-Eyed Seeing as a framework that gives equal consideration to Indigenous and Western ways of knowing so that neither dominates or undermines the other. She offers a pointed critique of positivism, the stance that historically dismissed Indigenous knowledge as unscientific, and argues that holding both worldviews together reshapes the very questions researchers ask about Indigenous health. The takeaway is that respectful pairing is the heart of the work, not a checklist for blending data.",
